<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/books-arts <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/books-arts" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - books-arts - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 28 日星期五 16:07:40 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Around the World With William F. Buckley Jr.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这位精力充沛的作家和编辑喜欢离开办公桌。他飞行、绘画、滑雪和航海——并写下了这一切。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590104182646082628"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825252?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">小威廉·F·巴克利 (William F. Buckley Jr.) 在他的帆船上，约。 1965年。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：杜鲁门摩尔/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB10950590414055573352804590104182646082628"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">马修·康蒂内蒂</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 11:26 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/around-the-world-with-william-f-buckley-jr-a291ad59"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>小威廉·巴克利 (William F. Buckley Jr.) 一直很忙。从1951年25岁出版《耶鲁的上帝与人》到2008年82岁去世，这位《国家评论》杂志的创始人、美国保守派知识分子运动的领袖很少停下来喘口气。除了撰写每周三次的报纸专栏和无数的杂志文章外，巴克利还发表演讲、主持电视节目“火线”、写了 57 本书、用钢琴和羽管键琴演奏、驾驶飞机、绘画、滑雪、环球旅行和驾着他的帆船横渡大洋。他一年的活动和经验比大多数人一个世纪所能容纳的还要多。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/6fefdd53-1819-413c-97b0-a3a496f1a16a.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>巴克利的敌人是乏味的。他以与反对全球共产主义和侵入性政府相同的强度来抵制懒惰。 “无聊是最致命的毒药，不言而喻，它对最舒适的人造成最严重的伤害，”他写道，并引用了索尔仁尼琴最令人难忘的人物之一：“伊万·杰尼索维奇遭受了一切——除了无聊。”巴克利从他的父亲（一位德克萨斯州石油商）那里继承了财富，但他并没有屈服于游手好闲。他的文集记录了数十年来对祖国政治、文化、社会和娱乐生活的持续参与。</p><p>今年夏天，我们有机会重温巴克利的智慧和对生活的热情。编辑兼学者比尔·米汉 (Bill Meehan) 将巴克利的旅行文章和散文收集在一本题为《入门》的书中。与此同时，出版商罗曼和利特菲尔德重新发行了巴克利四本航海书籍中的前两本——《空降》和《大西洋高中》——并由他的小说家儿子克里斯托弗进行了新的介绍。这些书令人愉快地提醒我们，这位著名的辩论家也是一位才华横溢的回忆录作家和健谈家。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a94f169b-f82a-46d9-8cd8-efa471193042.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>指出知识产权不再具有像巴克利那样团结的领导者或像巴克利那样伟大的个性，这已成为陈词滥调。这种观点虽然正确，但却忽视了他的吸引力的戏剧性和渴望的维度。今天，无论是右派还是左派，都没有像上世纪中叶的前辈那样以同样的广度和热情追求非政治利益和主题的作家。巴克利不仅对这一消息发表评论。他教导下一代，生活不仅仅是党派斗争。</p><p>巴克利具有非凡的能力，能够向观众传达他的热情并带动他们一起参与。你不必是政治保守派、飞行常客或水手，就能分享他冒险进入未知领域、经受意外风暴和在公海上航行的快乐。他的谈话风格引人入胜、信息丰富且健谈。</p><p>没有任何一个主题能够吸引巴克利的注意力。 “我被冒险所吸引，却被马拉松所排斥，”他写道。 “我可以被说服从飞机上跳下来，降落在死亡谷的一口井里；我永远不会被说服去徒步穿越死亡谷，或者就此而言，登上马特宏峰。对我来说，埃维尔·克尼维尔比长跑运动员更有意义。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/1a5034d1-f516-4ff9-9d8f-2bcc69824ffc.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>成为比尔·巴克利（Bill Buckley）令人兴奋，他渴望让其他人也能享受到乐趣。通过他精致的感性和高雅的品味来替代生活是一种乐趣。游艇上的鸡尾酒时光、东方快车上的美食晚餐、在瑞士格施塔德滑雪、探索泰坦尼克号残骸——巴克利的描述让读者能够进入我们大多数人永远不会去的地方。 “我倾向于乘坐头等舱旅行，”他在 1996 年发表的一篇有关航空旅行的文章中写道，“这要归功于我自己客户的热情好客，以及多年来我通过大量汗水培养起来的享乐主义倾向。”</p><p> “四处走走”的范围很广。巴克利访问以色列、意大利和苏联的详细记录中穿插着对行李重量限制和商业航班上缺少椒盐卷饼的哀叹。在一页上，他参观了水疗中心，并评估了慢跑与骑自行车的优点；接下来，他踏上了协和式飞机的环球之旅。累积的效果就像与一位有趣的用餐伙伴一起度过一个晚上。酒香四溢，谈笑风生。</p><p>巴克利是一位冠军名人。他对同事和对手的提及构成了 20 世纪 70 年代和 80 年代的名人录。年轻的读者可能很难辨认这些页面上出现的名人的名字，从演员大卫·尼文到文学评论家休·肯纳，从经济学家约翰·肯尼思·加尔布雷思到专栏作家安东尼·刘易斯和哈里特·范·霍恩。</p><p>这些被遗忘的人物和事件并不妨碍享受。它们邀请人们更多地了解前一个时代喧闹的知识生活。它们提醒我们，上个世纪的美国人受益于共享参考和共同经验的厚重中庸文化。</p><p>无论巴克利出国旅行多远，他总是回到他最喜欢的消遣：航海。 Meehan 先生收藏的第一件作品是 1958 年的船上作品，最后一件作品也是 2004 年的作品。巴克利一生中拥有四艘游艇：Panic、Suzy Wong、Cyrano 和 Patito。每艘船都出现在《Getting About》中，巴克利作为乘客登上、包租巡航或用作水肺潜水和游泳平台的许多其他船只也是如此。吸引巴克利来到船上的不仅是它们带来的身体和精神挑战，还有它们提供的自由感和可能性。他在《Getting About》中转载的一篇文章中写道：“海洋是地球上最后一个可以完全自发运动的区域。”</p><p> 《Airborne》首次出版于 1976 年，描述了西哈诺号 (Cyrano) 的一次跨大西洋巡航。他和船员于1975年5月30日从迈阿密出发，中途经停百慕大和亚速尔群岛，并于6月30日抵达西班牙马贝拉。旅程并不顺利。设备坏了。暴雨爆发。船有搁浅的危险。巴克利在这些挫折中微笑着，用海洋故事和格言迷住读者（“我最快乐的迷信是，如果我在咖啡里加糖精，我就可以吃热软糖圣代作为甜点”）。</p><p>陪伴巴克利的是他的嫂子、几个亲密的朋友和刚从耶鲁大学毕业的克里斯托弗。巴克利告诉他的同伴们记录他们的想法和印象。 《空降兵》的页面因引用他们的期刊，尤其是克里斯托弗的期刊而变得生动活泼。年轻的巴克利的天赋已经很平淡了。他直接、有力、简洁的声音与他父亲巴洛克式的散文相得益彰。 “比尔阿姨（克里斯托弗对凯瑟琳阿姨的昵称）在 B 舱的药箱旁边睡得很香，”克里斯托弗在一篇典型的日记中写道。 “美国医学会、加州红十字会和蓝盾的全部知识和技术都被塞进、压缩并分隔成一个深海渔具盒。”</p><p>对于比尔·巴克利来说，航海的目的不仅是为了到达目的地，也是为了享受良好的陪伴。幽默是通过的必要条件。 《空降兵》中的水手们举办派对、陷入困境、开玩笑、玩游戏。例如，无论谁喝完一瓶酒，都必须写下一份反共声明，将其放入瓶子内，然后将其扔到海里。 “有人贡献了。 。 。 “中央情报局将保证在收到此消息后进行一（1）次免费暗杀。” ”</p><p> 《空降奇兵》大获成功，激发了续集《大西洋高调》的灵感，讲述了巴克利在第一次航行五年后进行的第二次跨大西洋航行。几次缺席使得《大西洋高中》的吸引力略低于其前身。一方面，克里斯托弗失踪了——他正忙着写他的第一本书。更重要的是，船只不同。巴克利非常喜欢他翻新的西拉诺，以至于它成为了另一个角色，第一个叙事的参与者。</p><p>相比之下，“海神号”——“任何打算登船并留在船上的人都将其发音为天神号”——有另一个船主和自己的船长。巴克利在西拉诺号上带来的定制细节、家庭纽带和家的舒适感都消失了，取而代之的是不熟悉的船员、一名专业摄影师和一位生病的远方熟人。巴克利热爱航海的品质——自发性和友谊——被削弱了。</p><p>尽管如此，《大西洋高中》仍然包含了第一本书所没有的内容。巴克利用了一章的时间回复他的信件。他对写拒绝信的最佳方式提出了自己的看法：“关键是简洁——没有办法放纵扩张的冲动并继续手头的事情，除非你准备好受到严重的歧视——即，向[假设的贡献者]琼斯发送一封很长的信，并忽略接下来的二十封信。”他还指导如何最好地拒绝各种请求。他发现，尽管他不愿意增加日程安排，但他经常答应。 “最大的敌人是：1）年轻人（其中一些你无法拒绝），2）其他编辑。”即使在 Sealestial 上，巴克利也发现自己陷入了公共辩论和职业阴谋的世界。</p><p>事实上，他可能喜欢航海，因为航海可以集中他的注意力，限制他的行动并迫使他保持静止。 2004 年，他在《大西洋月刊》上写道：“当你在港口时，可能会有四个志趣相投的人围坐在桌子旁，一边吃喝聊天，一边听音乐、抽雪茄，还有风、冰雹和外面的温度。”面对和面对。在这里，在你安全的小锚地里，是大自然子宫中生活乐趣的复合体。”</p><p>这些幸福、宁静和沉思的时刻启发了巴克利。在《大西洋高中》的结尾，当旅程结束时，巴克利想独自一人在海狮号上。他在日记中提出了一些观察结果，但发现很难表达他的满足感。 “我现在无法解读这十几个单词，”他写道。 “它们难以辨认。但我知道他们说什么。知道他们表达什么。感激。”</p><p>巴克利的写作充满了这种感激之情。他对他的信仰、他的国家、他的家人、他的朋友、他的礼物和他的好运感到​​感激。正如这些书所表明的那样，他也给了我们其他人很多值得感激的东西。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。康蒂内蒂是美国企业研究所的高级研究员，也是《右派：美国保守主义的百年战争》一书的作者，该书现已出版平装本。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 15:26:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/around-the-world-with-william-f-buckley-jr-a291ad59</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/around-the-world-with-william-f-buckley-jr-a291ad59<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Project-State and Its Rivals’ Review: Making the Nation Work]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在 20 世纪初争夺全球主导地位的竞争中，各国政府接受了动员公民参与巨大努力的想法。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108000987149766"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825022?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">意大利法西斯党的宣传海报。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：环球历史档案馆/环球图像集团/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11786258192805913745104590108000987149766"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">保罗·肯尼迪</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 11:20 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-project-state-and-its-rivals-review-making-the-nation-work-3d73391"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> 19世纪下半叶，西方民族国家之间的生活和政治变得越来越复杂。推动这一趋势的无疑是快速发展的工业化及其诸多“连锁反应”。用大卫·兰德斯 (David Landes) 1969 年出版的书中的好话来说，大量新技术和快速经济增长是“不受束缚的普罗米修斯”，它们推动了各种变革，并以各种方式震撼了社会。反过来，各种类型的政客——右翼、左翼和中间派——都觉得他们必须做出回应。有些人直言不讳地反对任何新事物（旧的普鲁士保守派方法），有些人则彻底推翻了一切（列宁的方法）。其他人试图弄清楚如何改善民族国家的运作方式，履行其承诺并满足其公民的需求。然而，最后一个选择需要一个激进的国家，或者用某些社会科学家喜欢的另一个术语来说，“项目国家”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a2bbfa22-b941-49cf-b2ef-b4c974c2e5ec.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>查尔斯·迈尔（Charles Maier）最新的雄心勃勃的著作《项目国家及其竞争对手》概述了这种政体是如何形成的以及它们对世界意味着什么。 “项目国家没有什么硬性规定，”迈尔写道，“但它需要一定程度的自我意识野心。其领导人制定了他们认为远远超出普通行政管理的议程，无论是在社会变革还是国家权威方面。他们感受到了历史的召唤。”</p><p>随着20世纪初的大国相互竞争，它们的政府变得越来越积极：除了国内压力之外，竞争性的国际秩序也提供了内部改革的动力。例如，提高社会教育技能需要进行许多学校改革，或许还需要创建技术大学。创建一支由数百万强​​壮、健康的年轻人组成的国家军队意味着公共卫生的巨大改善。在第一次世界大战爆发之前，这种情况已经在一些国家（德意志帝国、爱德华七世时期的英国）发生，而这场巨大的冲突激起了许多其他国家对提高效率和进一步国家进步的需求。</p><p>战争引发的新意识形态和政体反过来又强化了这一趋势。例如，墨索里尼的法西斯意大利就是典型的项目国家，修建高速公路，排干蓬蒂沼泽的水，让意大利年轻人穿上军装。可以说，这就是罗斯福新政的愿景。希特勒的第三帝国在某种程度上是一个巨大的、扭曲的项目国家，就像斯大林的共产主义政权一样：一大批科研人员从事从农业改进到原子能等各个领域的工作，而数百万其他俄罗斯人则被派往苏联。古拉格所谓的“再教育”。</p><p>迈尔承认，“项目国家”的概念可以用来“描述未来半个世纪中相互激烈对立的政权的特征”。这些领导人的共同点是，他们“相信政治机构应该而且能够果断地重塑公民社会”。政治领导（通常具有超凡魅力）很重要，设计“项目”并为其进行宣传的公共知识分子也很重要。许多项目，例如林登·约翰逊的反贫困战争，其语言都带有某种军事色彩。</p><p>大国并不是唯一的项目国家；它们也是项目国家。他们只是最大的。在 20 世纪，还有许多其他的人。其中一些国家并不在发达的资本主义社会，而是在印度或巴西等大型发展中国家，那里的右翼或左翼改革派政府时不时地与积极主动的民政管理者一起推动变革，无论人民是否喜欢。 。</p><p>如此庞大而复杂的故事——实际上是“二十世纪和二十一世纪的新历史”——催生了一本庞大而复杂的书。但这对于迈尔先生来说是意料之中的，他是哈佛大学最有成就的现代历史学家之一。距离他向我们展示他的第一部巨著《重塑资产阶级欧洲：第一次世界大战后十年法国、德国和意大利的稳定》（1975）以来，已经过去了近 50 年。其他影片则以令人生畏的规律性紧随其后，其中许多都带有精辟的标题：《寻求稳定》（1987年）、《不可掌握的过去》（1988年）、《解散》（1997年）、《帝国之间》（2006年）、《利维坦2.0》（ 2014），“一旦在边界内”（2016）。他的学术广度总是令人印象深刻，他对社会变革——现代企业结构、大众政治、国际经济、种族和地区变体的研究也是如此。他经常引用法语、德语、意大利语和英语的书籍和其他著作。他可能会说，如果他的工作很复杂，有时甚至很困难，那是因为我们人类过去 125 年的斗争也是如此。</p><p> 《项目国家及其竞争对手》共 400 页，共 10 个大章节，大致按时间顺序排列；每一章都有进一步的细分，迈尔先生试图应对世界上发生的一切，比如 20 世纪 70 年代这样一个复杂的十年。坦率地说，非专业读者可能会对本书的规模和复杂性感到畏惧。</p><p>许多年前，在观察学者们如何争论另一个伟大时代（英国内战的到来）时，才华横溢的 JH Hexter 断言历史学家可以分为两大阵营——“Lumpers”，他们以广泛的主张和努力写作以及“分裂者”，他们喜欢向我们展示过去任何时期的许多变化和例外。</p><p>如果迈尔先生以“分裂者”的身份写作，那是因为他想忠实于自己关于现代世界正在发生的事情的广泛论点。他还想诚实地表达自己对于人类是否仍然可以以任何方式进步的深深不确定性。作者承认，如果政治自由被牺牲、强人获得权力、失望的人民放弃民主和社会自由，提高生活水平的经济措施根本不够。</p><p> 20 世纪的许多历史——尤其是那些在选民投票支持克林顿、布莱尔、默克尔和奥巴马政府的短暂而愉快的时代所写的历史——都描述了政治和社会成果的稳步上升。相比之下，迈尔先生的作品却在接近尾声时步履蹒跚。他认为撒切尔和里根等人物的“新自由主义”经济和政府改革，无论多么必要，都是反对“项目国家”的举措。共产主义欧洲的垮台也让某种政治弥赛亚主义名声扫地。 “如果历史在二十世纪末停止，”他写道，“法律的新精神——回忆一下孟德斯鸠的基本社会政治共识术语——将是傲慢的资本家和被认为是社会民主党人的融合，他们着迷于他们的发现市场。”并提醒读者，本书的完整标题是“项目国家及其竞争对手”。</p><p>但迈尔先生目前心目中的对手似乎并不是反政府的新自由主义者，而是新一代的政治家，他们对于如何利用自己的权力重塑自己的国家形象，似乎有着旧日那种趾高气扬的自信。社会。威权主义，无论是在东欧还是在非洲，它本身就可以是一个“项目”，或者至少通过其许多项目抓住了公众的思想。事实上，该书最后一章的标题是“民粹主义主张和威权主义的回归”。</p><p>因此，这本书的许多早期部分都充满了活力和智慧的优雅，最终却步履蹒跚地结束了。我认为，情况并不是作者本人已经耗尽了精力，而是他感觉到一两代人之前的进步主义假设（当然是他自己的假设）遭到了广泛的抵制。</p><p>他承认，莫迪、埃尔多安、博尔索纳罗、特朗普、欧尔班和普京等领导人的煽动性吸引力有很多是可以理解的，这让迈尔先生非常担心。他很诚实地认为，孟德斯鸠、斯密和密尔所预见的西方民主轨迹可能正在支离破碎。具有讽刺意味的是，正是迈尔先生对我们民主秩序的脆弱性以及对 21 世纪第三个十年中反民主冲动的相当大力量的公开担忧，使得《项目国家及其竞争对手》成为一本会持续。</p><p>它具有弗里茨·斯特恩（Fritz Stern）的《文化绝望的政治》（1961）和阿普·桑顿（AP Thornton）的《帝国理念及其敌人》（1959）等著作的“宏大性”。但它比其他作品更重要，因为它是我们这个动荡时代的知识标记。虽然他坚持早期的希望，即项目国家（以各种方式）将推进我们人类的朝圣之路，但他也不愿意将进步的反对者视为一种短暂的现象，注定要被扔进历史的垃圾箱。他们存在于许多国家，他们的政治和社会阻力是真实存在的。如果这本书的最后几页摇摆不定，那是因为迈尔先生担心我们的民主世界出现摇摇欲坠的迹象。</p><p>读者有权问，他的说法完全错误吗？这位审稿人并不这么认为。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。肯尼迪是耶鲁大学历史学教授，也是许多研究的作者，包括《大国的兴衰》。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 15:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-project-state-and-its-rivals-review-making-the-nation-work-3d73391</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-project-state-and-its-rivals-review-making-the-nation-work-3d73391<category>图书</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Tom Lake’ Review: Spotlight on the Past]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>安·帕切特的小说讲述了三姐妹寄居在自家农场里，聆听母亲成年后的戏剧故事。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590110423217352484"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824962?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Khanh Bui/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590110423217352484"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">海勒·麦卡尔</span>平</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 11:17 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tom-lake-review-spotlight-on-the-past-62bd0ea"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> “有人在活着的时候意识到过生命吗？——每时每刻？”这个问题是由 25 岁的艾米丽·韦伯·吉布斯 (Emily Webb Gibbs) 在桑顿·怀尔德 (Thornton Wilder) 的《我们的小镇》的最后一幕中提出的。艾米丽·韦伯·吉布斯 (Emily Webb Gibbs) 最近因难产而去世，安·帕切特 (Ann Patchett) 的第九部小说光芒四射，在该小说中，怀尔德 1938 年广受欢迎的戏剧占据了重要地位。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/7bc6d6f7-2d63-47bd-89ae-89a4934b4db7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> 《汤姆·莱克》的叙述者、出生于新罕布什尔州的拉拉·凯尼森 (Lara Kenison) 非常自然地扮演了怀尔德笔下的新罕布什尔州小镇女孩这个角色，她在 16 岁到 25 岁之间曾三次扮演这个角色——这与艾米丽的年龄相同。 《我们的小镇》涵盖的生活。劳拉的前两次表演是在高中和大学期间；最后一次是1988年在密歇根州汤姆湖剧团。</p><p>三十年后，当劳拉的三个成年女儿回到家中位于密歇根州北部的苹果和樱桃农场以躲避新冠病毒大流行时，她想起了玩“我们的小镇”的经历是如何改变她的生活的。尽管面临当前的世界危机，劳拉还是很高兴能让她的女儿们回家——尤其是因为，在封锁期间缺乏季节性工人，一家人必须自己收获水果。为了打发时间，劳拉亲自采摘一排又一排的甜樱桃，同意向他们讲述她最近在新闻中与一位演员的恋情，这位演员是她在汤姆湖遇到的。彼得·杜克 (Peter Duke) 名声大噪，而劳拉 (Lara) 虽然是一颗冉冉升起的新星，但在那年夏天发生了一些令人不安的事件后，决定退出演艺圈。</p><p>樱桃园里的三姐妹？我脑海中浮现的剧作家不是桑顿·怀尔德，而是安东·契诃夫。事实上，《汤姆湖》与契诃夫的《樱桃园》和《三姐妹》相呼应，包括保住家庭土地的挑战、通过工作寻求有意义的生活的决心，以及年轻女性对逃离郊区的厌倦和渴望。 ——尽管拉拉的两个小女儿不是怀念莫斯科，而是怀念她们中断的追求、兽医学校和演艺生涯。 （她的大女儿艾米丽将接管农场。）</p><p>尽管具有契诃夫式的主题，《汤姆湖》更多地归功于《我们的小镇》，怀尔德曾在序言中简洁地将其描述为“试图为我们日常生活中最小的事件找到高于一切价格的价值”。帕切特女士的小说颂扬了日常生活中的乐趣，比如在果园和密歇根湖大特拉弗斯湾岸边的树林中看到 80 英尺高的铁杉，或者劳拉重聚的女儿们唱着“晚安，晚安，在果园里度过了漫长的一天后，他们互相碰撞着上床睡觉时说“晚安”。</p><p>劳拉讲述了一个关于她刚刚起步的演艺生涯和成年之路的曲折而悠闲的故事。她在她的第一部业余作品中度过了一段甜蜜的时光，描述了当地城镇居民可笑的试镜，这教会了她“如何在世界上展示自己”，并在好莱坞工作了一段时间，在那里她最大的兴奋是在好莱坞工作。豪华轿车。当她沿着记忆的小巷漫步时，她的女儿们变得焦躁不安，对她与杜克的风流韵事的有趣细节感到不耐烦。 “这三个女孩现在都二十多岁了，尽管她们不断进步，表面上也得到了解放，但她们对一个不关于英俊、著名男人的故事不感兴趣，”劳拉说。 “尽管如此，我是他们的母亲，他们明白，他们必须忍受我才能找到他。”</p><p>劳拉坚决按照自己的节奏继续讲述她的故事，“她很清楚，他们等待听到的部分是我永远不会告诉他们的部分。”她对早期事迹的投入可能也会考验读者的耐心，但缓慢的构建是值得等待的。</p><p>事实上，其结果是叙事和家长控制的大师班。帕切特女士轻松地在过去和现在之间滑动，操纵关键信息发布的速度和时间以达到最大效果——例如一个角色的身份，以及另一个角色过早死亡的消息。劳拉向读者承认，但不向女儿承认，她决定隐瞒一些细节，主要是性方面的细节。 “我希望他们认为我比以前更好了，”她说道，“我想告诉他们真相，以防真相有用。这两种欲望并不能完美共存。 。 ”。后来，劳拉与读者分享了与杜克的一次令人羞愧的遭遇，她决定永远不会让家人知道这件事。 “我给我的女儿们看了导演剪辑版，”她说。</p><p>在她最畅销的第四部小说《美声唱法》中，帕切特创造了一个社会的缩影，这个社会由一群南美恐怖分子以及他们劫持的知名高管、政客和歌剧歌手组成。她所做的事情与夏季戏剧中强制的团结和压缩的强度类似，劳拉在晚上扮演无辜的艾米丽，白天排练山姆·谢泼德的热气腾腾的“爱情傻瓜”（其中她感到悲惨地脱离了自己的舒适区），并且她把每一分钟的空闲时间都花在与魅力四射但精神不稳定的搭档在湖里或床单之间游泳。</p><p> 《汤姆湖》用足够的细节来传达樱桃种植的严酷和压力，让《联邦》和《荷兰之家》的作者继续从事她真正擅长的业务：监控家庭的起起落落和具有敏感性的群体动态。帕切特女士是一位非常热情的作家，她经常写到孩子们在混合家庭中努力寻找自己的位置的故事。在《汤姆·莱克》中，正如她在《这是幸福婚姻的故事》中可爱的文章一样，她证明了幸福、有凝聚力的家庭可以和不幸、破碎的家庭一样有趣。她的小说不仅讲述了有时令人不安的母女关系，还讲述了即使是适应良好的年轻人也很难接受这样一个事实：他们的父母过着充满梦想、激情、乏味、胜利、错误、心碎的生活——是的， 、性——在他们出生之前。</p><p>在《我们的小镇》中，艾米丽在格罗弗角墓地的一位已故邻居痛苦地评论说，对大多数人来说，活着根本不是用心生活，而是“在无知的云中走来走去”，“把时间浪费在浪费时间上”。尽管你还有一百万年。”</p><p>劳拉希望向她的女儿们传递的信息是，虽然她年轻时可能无知并被激情蒙蔽了双眼，但多年来她已经逐渐理解了怀尔德比赛的教训。 “这并不是说我没有意识到世界上的苦难和即将到来的更多苦难，”她说，“而是我知道苦难存在于潮湿的草地和最近被雨水洗刷过的明亮的蓝天旁边。美丽和痛苦同样真实。”</p><p>在一段不祥的时期与家人隔离的帕切特女士，她极具魅力的性格决心充分欣赏转瞬即逝的瞬间，“看到这一切，并尽可能长时间地保留它”。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。麦卡尔平定期为《华尔街日报》、《基督教科学箴言报》和 NPR.org 审阅书籍。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 15:17:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tom-lake-review-spotlight-on-the-past-62bd0ea</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tom-lake-review-spotlight-on-the-past-62bd0ea<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Science Fiction & Fantasy: ‘Scarlet’ by Genevieve Cogman]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>以法国大革命期间为背景的奇幻作品在高贵吸血鬼的世界中重新演绎了猩红色皮姆佩内尔的故事。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590110411906045270"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824891?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">伊丽莎白·维热·勒布伦的《法国王后玛丽·安托瓦内特与一朵玫瑰》（1783 年）。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Photo12/Universal Images Group/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590110411906045270"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">莉兹·布拉斯韦尔</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 11:15 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/science-fiction-fantasy-scarlet-by-genevieve-cogman-8098c5de"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>夏天没有什么真正的假期，所以希望你们都度过了一个愉快的巴士底日！我和家人一起玩纸牌游戏“断头台”并阅读吉纳维芙·科格曼的《猩红》来庆祝。广受欢迎的《看不见的图书馆》系列的作者现在通过生动地复述奥奇男爵夫人的《猩红皮姆佩内尔》故事来探讨文学界最血腥的两个主题：法国大革命，当然还有吸血鬼。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/35151395-a582-4333-8362-6a25f60ef140.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>埃莉诺·道尔顿 (Eleanor Dalton) 在贝辛男爵夫人索菲夫人 (Lady Sophie, Baroness of Basing) 的英国家庭工作，她的任务是完成一个慢慢晋升的仆人可能会遇到的各种中级苦差事。她梦想有一天成为一名裁缝或刺绣师，但现在埃莉诺很高兴她不再是一名洗碗女仆——这份工作的职责包括打开静脉，这样这位女士就可以时不时地喝一杯她的血。在这个版本的历史中，贵族中有吸血鬼——他们被称为“血统”。 （在我们的世界里，这个令人回味的术语被用来形容罗伯斯庇尔的嗜血恐怖统治。）</p><p>埃莉诺令人惊叹的缝纫天赋使她在同龄人中脱颖而出，但她还有一个至今为止一直不为人知的特征：一张可能被误认为是玛丽·安托瓦内特的脸。进入猩红皮姆佩内尔联盟，这是一个秘密的贵族男孩俱乐部，致力于将法国贵族从断头台上拯救出来。他们发现了相似之处，并迫使埃莉诺参与营救被监禁的女王的计划。埃莉诺答应了，因为她认为贵族不一定应该得到这样的命运。她还被许诺拥有一家自己的商店，作为对她提供帮助的奖励。方便-<em>简单</em>！</p><p>当然，事实并非如此。埃莉诺遭到愤怒的暴徒、精神错乱的远古吸血鬼的袭击，最糟糕的是，公共安全委员会的阿尔芒·肖维林。除了所有贵族的死亡之外，这位“革命者”唯一想要的就是为他自己和他的女儿提供一个安全的职位，以及一座豪宅。还有权力。</p><p> Besides the constant threats of violence, Eleanor has to endure the social and emotional repercussions of being with the League of the Scarlet Pimpernel, but not <em>in</em> it. As a woman and a member of the common people, she has to mind her step around her aristocratic co-conspirators. When she dares to correct their presumptions about how the world works they can get testy: Lord Charles in particular always nastily puts her in her place (but he also might be falling in love with her, another problem).</p><p> Eleanor comes to realize that what she wants more than anything else is control over her own life, something which the nobility, vampires and even the sans-culottes deny her. It isn&#39;t until Eleanor is accidentally united with the bodiless spirit of a sorceress long dead—a state that comes with problems both like and unlike Eleanor&#39;s—that our heroine begins to see a way out.</p><p> “Scarlet” is a satisfying, historically accurate adventure that doesn&#39;t lean too heavily on its one fantastical invention. Two fangs up, and <em>vive la révolution!</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 15:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/science-fiction-fantasy-scarlet-by-genevieve-cogman-8098c5de</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/science-fiction-fantasy-scarlet-by-genevieve-cogman-8098c5de<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Slip’ Review: Dockside Visionaries]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>在 20 世纪 50 年代华尔街阴影下的海滨地区，埃尔斯沃斯·凯利 (Ellsworth Kelly)、罗伯特·印第安纳 (Robert Indiana) 和其他人找到了创作艺术的地方。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108492145796672"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825015?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1961 年，埃尔斯沃斯·凯利 (Ellsworth Kelly) 在他位于 Coenties Slip 的曼哈顿工作室里。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：弗里茨·戈罗</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108492145796672"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">汉密尔顿·凯恩</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 10:42 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-slip-review-dockside-visionaries-574a78d7"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>曼哈顿下城的斯莱普斯（Slips）——东河上以前的船舶泊位，现在被垃圾填埋场铺成了街道和广场——在我们的历史记忆中，唤起了 19 世纪的高大船只和枝形吊灯，当时的贸易和纽约港为这座城市的发展提供了动力。爆炸性增长。在摩天大楼的森林中，斯利普斯的长方形空间和倾斜的光线在视觉上显得神秘，并且在某些地方可以看到汹涌的水流和布鲁克林的全景。南街海港是对过去的颂歌。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/46c38dea-9866-4e1e-b7ae-f47aa99e4c66.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>普鲁登斯·佩弗 (Prudence Peiffer) 在其精彩而清晰的作品《The Slip》中展示了一群艺术家，他们在 20 世纪 50 年代末和 60 年代，即纵帆船和护卫舰搬迁数十年后，居住在 Coenties Slip 沿线（现已成为珍珠街附近金融区的一部分）到哈德逊河。这些艺术家不得不过着廉价的生活，蹲在废弃仓库的阁楼里，辛勤地创作画布和雕塑。在抽象表现主义的突破之后，他们想象出了新的可能性。</p><p>纽约现代艺术博物馆的编辑佩弗女士以汉斯·纳穆斯 1958 年拍摄的一张照片开始了她的叙述，这是一张在 3-5 Coenties 的柏油纸屋顶上拍摄的集体照。他们的姿势体现了拍摄对象之间的轻松自在，源于纽约年轻而雄心勃勃的浪漫。 《失足》围绕同性恋埃尔斯沃斯·凯利和异性恋杰克·杨格曼之间的亲密友谊展开，他们是二战后在巴黎相识的前美国士兵，但佩弗女士将他们的关系放在了更广泛的圈子里：杨格曼的法裔黎巴嫩人妻子，女演员德尔菲娜·塞里格 (Delphine Seyrig)，在阿兰·雷奈 (Alain Resnais) 的《马里昂巴德的去年》中注定会获得不朽的赛璐珞；才华横溢的罗伯特·印第安纳（原名罗伯特·克拉克），曾是凯利的短暂情人； Lenore Tawney，从事纺织品实验；艾格尼丝·马丁 (Agnes Martin) 是一位隐匿精神分裂症的游牧极简主义者；明尼苏达州长大的詹姆斯·罗森奎斯特（James Rosenquist），他的图形预示着波普艺术。还有一些令人兴奋的客串，例如贾斯珀·琼斯 (Jasper Johns) 和罗伯特·劳森伯格 (Robert Rauschenberg)，他们的公寓就在拐角处。 （他们保持着礼貌的距离。）</p><p>对于居民来说，科恩蒂斯位于曼哈顿郊外的“市中心”。冒险穿过前街就是“进入城市”。他们的大部分作品都反对抽象表现主义，抽象表现主义在战后美国艺术中占主导地位，本身就是对画架传统的拒绝。杰克逊·波洛克 (Jackson Pollock) 1956 年在长岛发生的致命车祸，通过讲述一个天才被自己的恶魔摧毁的悲剧神话，证实了“Ab Ex”作为主流美学的地位。科恩蒂斯社区更喜欢安静的生活，而不是格林威治村雪松酒馆的“喧闹、好战”场景，格林威治村是 Ab Ex 人群最喜欢去的地方。相比之下，扬格曼说，他和他的朋友是“一群来自内陆地区的新教徒”。他们在海员教堂研究所顶上标出了几处仅装饰着银杏树的朴素街区和一座灯塔，以纪念泰坦尼克号的沉没。</p><p>在这里，他们探索了一系列的思想和方法，但他们是“一个不是通过构图、技术甚至哲学原则（如抽象表现主义）聚集在一起的团体，也不是通过一种特定的反应或综合文化时刻的方式，如波普艺术，”佩弗女士评论道。反思纳穆斯的屋顶照片，她问道：“如果我们考虑艺术史上的群体而不是基于共享的地方，会怎么样？如果不是技术或风格，而是地方精神决定了关键时刻，又会怎样呢？”</p><p>佩弗女士在每个人物的简介和该社区丰富的历史之间切换，追溯到殖民时期：“斯利普是一个简朴的、几乎被遗忘的地方，是一条在船蛆和爬虫出没的码头上的死胡同。”在它的变形中，她看到了“这座岛的整个历史就在它的鹅卵石上”。该地点从早期起就是一个商业中心，“由奴隶建造，革命会议就在珍珠街举行”，并在梅尔维尔的《白鲸记》中出现过。在贸易周期中，滑坡经历了“海运和轻工业的繁荣与萧条以及繁荣与萧条”。</p><p>虽然佩弗女士与过去的转变有时会令人不舒服，但她强调了科恩蒂家贫困的船员与几码之外的华尔街之间的讽刺对比，以及两者之间更微妙的联系。从罗森奎斯特到德库宁再到沃霍尔，战后画家经常接受商业插画师和广告牌设计师的培训。欧洲画家借鉴了数百年的发光明暗对比和消失点遗产，而美国人则不同，他们自己利用这些材料，没有任何表现的义务。</p><p>艾格尼丝·马丁，这位中年纯粹主义者，把干旱的新墨西哥州换成了港口的雾气。佩弗女士在马丁不安的动作中发现了她作品的核心对立的关键：“在城市和沙漠之间来回穿梭，强调了她一生中一个更广泛的主题，即分离和社区之间的主题，模仿了美国本身。 。 。城市的动力和田园的宁静，资本主义的欲望和加尔文主义的克制。”与此同时，Lenore Tawney 在编织方面的创新——她发明了新的方法、工具和形式——将织物提升为讲述故事的媒介。</p><p>佩弗女士关于埃尔斯沃斯·凯利和罗伯特·印第安纳的章节是她最好的。作为亚历山大·考尔德 (Alexander Calder) 的得意门生，凯利 (Kelly) 痴迷于色彩——对他来说，“世界上有一千种黄色”——而他大胆的画布是对原色的赞歌。他的植物画现在是博物馆的主要展品。印第安纳十几岁的时候就学过拉丁语，并且热衷于被称为“赫姆斯”的希腊雕像，这是一种带有男性头像和雕刻生殖器的古典柱子。他用在附近捡来的废料更新了这些雕塑，并添加了<em>“CHIEF”、“AHAB”、“TUG</em> ”等词语，暗示了他的海滨环境。</p><p>到 20 世纪 60 年代中期，Coenties 艺术家已经分散到其他地方。虽然佩弗女士的书并没有实现其副标题所声称的“这张纸条”“永远改变了美国艺术”，但它仍然生动地描述了美国历史上的一个重要时刻。曼哈顿下城的边缘仍然有一些乔治亚风格的建筑，但它们被玻璃塔所掩盖，玻璃塔是金融业入侵的标志。佩弗女士写道：“生活在滑坡上就等于生活在历史的重写本中，现在的情况从未完全确定。”重新出发的机会永远在召唤。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。该隐是《这个男孩的信仰：美南浸信会成长笔记》一书的作者。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-slip-review-dockside-visionaries-574a78d7</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-slip-review-dockside-visionaries-574a78d7<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The 272’ Review: Slaves of Georgetown]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着 1830 年代棉花盈利能力达到新的高度，华盛顿特区的大学将剩余的奴隶卖到了南方腹地。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590108160471514500"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825074?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1860 年代，弗吉尼亚州亚历山大的富兰克林和阿姆菲尔德奴隶监狱中的一名妇女。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Buyenlarge/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590108160471514500"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">弗格斯·M·博德维奇 (Fergus M. Bordewich)</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 10:39 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-272-review-slaves-of-georgetown-4d7cd74c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> 1838 年 11 月，弗吉尼亚州亚历山大的码头上演了令人悲伤但又熟悉的一幕：奴隶贩子将数十名被奴役的男女和儿童赶上一艘开往遥远的路易斯安那州棉花种植园的船。他们是乔治敦学院耶稣会士为支撑学校不稳定的财务状况而出售的第一批 272 名美国黑人。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/bce49949-51fb-477d-b16b-ccba2c689879.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>纽约大学新闻学教授雷切尔·斯沃恩斯 (Rachel Swarns) 于 2016 年在《纽约时报》工作时首次了解到这个长期被遗忘的故事。在《272》中，她将早期的报道放大为生动而引人入胜的叙述，揭示了这些悲惨事件的复杂性，并在可能的情况下追踪了奴隶本身的命运。</p><p>斯沃恩斯女士认为，奴隶制对于美国罗马天主教会的发展至关重要。 “一个多世纪以来，”她写道，教会“依靠买卖和奴役黑人来奠定其基础，支持其神职人员并推动其扩张。”她说，奴隶劳动的收益被用来建造美国第一所天主教大学和大教堂等机构。</p><p> 1634 年，在巴尔的摩勋爵塞西尔·卡尔弗特的主持下，来自英国的天主教徒抵达北美，并在马里兰州波托马克河上建立了自己的殖民地。他最终将约 20,000 英亩的皇家土地赠予耶稣会士，这些财产后来演变成了奴隶种植园网络。斯沃恩斯女士告诉我们，安·乔伊斯 (Ann Joice) 是殖民地最早的劳工之一，她是一位自由的英国黑人妇女，于 1676 年左右作为契约仆人来到这里，被迫沦为奴隶，她的后代也受到奴役，直到内战期间获得自由。</p><p>几代人以来，马里兰州一直是美国农村天主教人口的中心。他们的精神需求主要由从欧洲派遣的牧师来满足，直到 1791 年乔治城学院（美国第一所天主教高等教育机构）开学为止。它的创建是由约翰·卡罗尔神父推动的，他是当地一个有权有势的地主家庭的后裔。 （乔治敦是马里兰州一个繁荣的河港，刚刚并入哥伦比亚特区。）从一开始，该学院就吸引了来自非天主教家庭的学生，其中包括乔治华盛顿的侄孙，但它在财务上陷入困境。 1830年代，充满活力的托马斯·穆勒迪神父（土生土长的弗吉尼亚人，曾在罗马学习过的耶稣会士）领导下的新领导层开始通过将耶稣会士拥有的一项丰富资产：奴隶货币化来稳定学院。</p><p>一些耶稣会士表示担心他们的奴隶可能会被卖给“异教徒”，但他们对出售同胞的道德问题基本上保持沉默，因为他们中的大多数人一生都生活在教会的土地上。尽管欧洲和美国北部对奴隶制的谴责日益增多，穆勒迪却嘲笑“美国人对解放的狂热”。</p><p>马勒迪与一位富有的国会议员亨利·约翰逊达成了一项协议，他想要人手在路易斯安那州的大片种植园工作，并同意批量购买耶稣会的奴隶。约翰逊是一名非天主教徒，按照当时的标准，他被认为是相对仁慈的：他同意不拆散家庭，并确保被奴役者能够接触天主教神职人员，他只是有时兑现承诺。</p><p>耶稣会奴隶的出售促进了当时美国正在发生的经济调整，因为大西洋中部传统的烟草种植经济的重要性逐渐减弱，而棉花生产的盈利能力飙升至新的高度。总共约有一百万奴隶被迫离开上南部的家园，在从阿拉巴马州到德克萨斯州的棉田里劳作。</p><p>与此同时，随着移民从爱尔兰和德国涌入北部城市，美国的天主教人口激增，对牧师、教堂和学校产生了前所未有的需求，并将该宗教的人口重心从马里兰州农村转移开。斯沃恩斯女士写道，乔治敦的耶稣会士向其他地方的天主教社区输送资金、教师和物资，在此过程中“将自己从一个被称为马里兰州最大奴隶主之一的组织转变为一个后来成为天主教教育代名词的组织。”她说，1838 年的大规模拍卖是“关键的转折点”。</p><p>出售的利润流入耶稣会士的账户，最终总计超过 13 万美元，按今天的美元计算约为 450 万美元。这笔钱使耶稣会士能够投资国库券和债券，产生足够的收入来支持新学校，包括密苏里州的圣路易斯大学、马萨诸塞州的圣十字学院和巴尔的摩的洛约拉学院。斯沃恩斯女士声称，“如果没有奴隶，我们今天所知道的美国天主教会就不会存在。”</p><p> 2021年，经过与耶稣会奴隶后裔多年有时紧张的谈判，乔治城大学同意代表他们设立一个1亿美元的基金：其中一半将分配给从事种族和解的组织；四分之一分配给后代学生的奖学金；其余的则专门用于满足年老体弱的后代的紧急需求。</p><p> “272”既不是大规模赔偿的论点，也不是针对天主教会的争论。虽然斯沃恩斯女士的心关心着被奴役者和他们的悲惨命运，这是可以理解的，但她的叙述公正，阐明了耶稣会士的务实动机，并从近乎遗忘的状态中恢复了故事中心被奴役者的生活。</p><p>除了斯沃恩斯女士为穆勒迪神父和其他耶稣会士刻画的清晰肖像之外，我们还见到了男男女女，比如重男轻女的黑人种植园工头哈利·马奥尼（Harry Mahoney），他在 1812 年战争期间藏匿了马里兰州牧师的积蓄，免遭英国军队的掠夺，还有他的非洲人。 - 出生的妻子，安娜。我们也见到了他们的孩子：比比亚娜，被卖给路易斯安那州的奴隶主；罗伯特，人到中年就会被评价为“没有价值”；安娜则留在马里兰州并活到了 20 世纪。</p><p>捕捉更多奴隶的生活是一项艰巨的挑战，因为他们在奴隶主的记录中很少只以单一的名字出现。斯沃恩斯女士出色地挖掘档案和口述历史，梳理出隐藏的联系和传记细节。特别是，她成功地为安·乔伊斯的后裔编织了一幅引人注目的挂毯，虽然不一定完整，我们很高兴地得知，他们在马里兰州和路易斯安那州克服困难而茁壮成长，并在他们的祖先到达这些地区 350 年后重新发现了彼此。海岸，共同努力说服乔治城大学正视其完整的历史。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。博德维奇是《三K党战争：尤利西斯·S·格兰特和拯救重建之战》一书的作者，该书将于十月出版。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:39:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-272-review-slaves-of-georgetown-4d7cd74c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-272-review-slaves-of-georgetown-4d7cd74c<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>教育</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>教育</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Mysteries: Three Novels of Domestic Suspense]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>劳拉·利普曼的《舞会妈妈》、梅根·艾伯特的《当心女人》和苏珊·艾萨克斯的《坏坏西摩·布朗》。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590111960757872040"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="495" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824507?width=860&amp;height=495" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590111960757872040"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/tom-nolan" itemprop="url" rel="author">汤姆·诺兰</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 28 日上午 10:38 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries-three-novels-of-domestic-suspense-3d80fae3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>劳拉·利普曼 (Laura Lippman) 的最新小说《舞会妈妈》以巴尔的摩妇女安布尔·格拉斯 (Amber Glass) 为中心，她的生活因二十年前发生的事件而伤痕累累。学校舞会当晚，安布尔在酒店房间里昏倒了，醒来时发现身边只有她早产儿的毫无生气的尸体。她因婴儿的死亡而受到指责，入狱服刑并自我流放到新奥尔良。现在她回到了郊区的老家，卖掉了家里的老房子，开了一家美术馆。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/a7ddabb2-428b-4ec7-868c-4089704df6d8.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>那天晚上抛弃她去追求另一个女孩的“流氓爸爸”乔·辛普森现在怎么样了？乔结婚后成为一名雄心勃勃的房地产经纪人。没过多久，他就注意到了安布尔的新画廊，并想知道：“如果他现在能成为她的朋友——这难道不是一种救赎吗？”</p><p> 《舞会妈妈》的时间线在现在和过去之间切换，从不同的角度来看。随着李普曼女士讲述重要信息，引发读者的惊讶，读者的同情心从一个角色转移到另一个角色。</p><p> “如果你想拥有未来，”安布尔反思道，“你就必须放弃过去。”但如果你的缺点和冲动如此根深蒂固，以至于你注定要重蹈覆辙怎么办？长期以来，李普曼女士一直被认为是情节和阐述大师，多年来一直在提供心理上丰富的因果报应片段。即使是她最挑剔的粉丝也会忍不住认为《舞会妈妈》是她迄今为止最好的书之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/8ddf541e-5168-4e69-9061-49777d718253.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>梅根·阿博特的《小心女人》将浪漫悬疑带到了情节剧的边缘。这本书讲述了纽约教师杰西的痛苦经历，她与一位艺术家结婚，然后在怀孕后与他一起前往密歇根州的上半岛看望他丧偶的父亲。她对她的配偶杰德了解不多，但她高兴到了迷信的地步：“在某些方面，感觉就像是如此相爱——你必须隐藏它……” 。 。你是在挑战命运，或者什么的。”</p><p>杰德似乎不愿回到他母亲在生下他时去世的地方。他已经有10多年没有回家了。 “我们可以掉头回去，”他在开车时建议道，“解释一下这不是一个好时机。孩子快来了就不行了。”但杰德随后否认他说过这样的话；他坚称杰西一定是在做梦。</p><p>阿博特女士讲故事的天赋在这里得到了很好的体现。我们从第一页就被吸引住了，很快就被迷住了。和杰西一样，我们也被杰德退休的父亲阿什医生所吸引，他是一位渴望让儿媳安心的贵族绅士。但医生和儿子之间关系紧张，他所居住的偏远社区也存在令人不安的孤立感。</p><p> “这里的人们，我们不干涉，”医生沉默寡言的看护人解释道。 “我们保守秘密。我们只管自己的事。 。 。 。你看，你可能会死，但可能没有人知道。”在九个幽闭恐怖的日日夜夜中，这种令人毛骨悚然的感觉更加强烈。令人震惊的家庭揭露带来不祥的恐惧感。无论人们是否对这本书的离奇结局感到满意，阿博特女士无可否认地给我们带来了一个我们永远不会忘记的故事。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/d1c06a88-b667-43fe-baa8-5059a575c482.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>苏珊·艾萨克斯的《坏坏西摩·布朗》是由前联邦调查局特工科里·盖勒和她的父亲、退休的纽约警察局侦探丹·肖特兰主演的系列剧的第二部。西摩·布朗（Seymour Brown）是一位纽约会计师，他因洗钱而名利双收。他和他的妻子在一场故意放火的房屋火灾中丧生，他们五岁的女儿阿普丽尔逃了出来。</p><p>几十年后，现为罗格斯大学电影研究教授的阿普丽尔向科里的父亲寻求帮助。她刚刚在一场她确信有人企图杀害她的袭击中幸存下来。这次袭击可能与她父母悬而未决的谋杀案有关吗？前侦探丹多年来一直与艾普丽尔交换圣诞贺卡，他抓住这个机会重新审视“他最悬而未决的案件”。</p><p>新冠疫情爆发后，科里的父母与她和她的丈夫一起住在长岛。科里最近在一次绑架中幸存下来（请参阅 2019 年的“知己知彼”），她很高兴与大家共同努力，将阿普丽尔从过去和现在的创伤中解救出来。</p><p> “让人们谈论是我最擅长的，”科里声称。作为一名叙述者，她本人是一位令人敬畏的健谈者，像普鲁斯特一样慷慨地讲述细节，像郊区的山鲁佐德一样充满轶事。她和她的父亲组成了一个优秀的团队，汇集资源并吸引了许多前同事和客座专家来协助他们。他们需要尽可能多的帮助来对抗最顽固的恶棍并拯救他们勇敢可爱的客户。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries- Three-novels-of-domestic-suspense-3d80fae3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/mysteries- Three-novels-of-domestic-suspense-3d80fae3<author><![CDATA[Tom Nolan]]></author><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Hive’ Review: Faces in the Crowd]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Nobel laureate Camilo José Cela&#39;s novel unveiled life in Madrid during the Franco era, via a rich blend of voices and personalities. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108540615376652"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824858?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Universal History Archive/Universal Images/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590108540615376652"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Boyd Tonkin</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 10:31 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hive-review-fiction-madrid-faces-in-the-crowd-399854da"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Late at night, in the chilly winter of Madrid in 1943, lonely strollers drift into the movie theaters. They watch “pictures filled with attractive, poetic names that pose vast human enigmas which are not always deciphered, or answered at all.” The huge, swarming cast of “The Hive,” which the Spanish writer Camilo José Cela published in 1951, trip over those “vast human enigmas” as they try to make sense of their own discordant and disconnected lives. But life is tough, time short, money scarce. Even if love, pity or wonder briefly stir them, every citizen has a job to finish, a bill to pay, a date to meet. Passersby feel sorry for the dog crushed by a taxi in the Calle de Torrijos but “everyone goes his own way.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/04e109c5-2780-480d-bf20-300f91662547.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Throughout the 20th century, the shock of big-city life convulsed not only newly urbanized societies but their literature. Landmark frescoes of metropolitan hubbub and social fragmentation emerged from cities old and new, from the Dublin of Joyce&#39;s “Ulysses” to Alfred Döblin&#39;s “Berlin Alexanderplatz” and the New York of John Dos Passos&#39;s “Manhattan Transfer.” (Cela and Dos Passos shared an inspiration in the Basque novelist Pío Baroja.) Once a proud imperial hub, the Madrid of Cela&#39;s seething panorama has slipped into anxious, threadbare insecurity after Spain&#39;s ruinous and fratricidal civil war. On its hectic streets his throng of strivers, grafters, grifters and chancers sweat to get ahead, or just get by, while “something like sorrow floats in the air and strikes into people&#39;s hearts.”</p><p> Born in Galicia, with English, Italian and local ancestry, Cela (1916-2002) had scandalized the Spanish literary scene with the bleak determinism of his 1942 debut, “The Family of Pascual Duarte,” a murderer&#39;s confession often bracketed with Camus&#39;s “The Stranger.” Yet the future Nobel laureate in literature (in 1989) was never a straightforward radical. He fought for the nationalists in the Civil War and served as a censor for Franco&#39;s victorious regime. Ironically, the Spanish authorities banned “The Hive” all the same for its sexual frankness; it first appeared in Buenos Aires. By 1953, the scholar JM Cohen had translated it into English with the help of the exiled Spanish author Arturo Barea.</p><p> In one of the seven prefaces to various editions that front James Womack&#39;s savory new translation, Cela reckons that his novel has 160 characters. Other critics have counted over 200, in a mere 262 pages. Over three winter days, as Hitler&#39;s forces falter on distant battlefields, Cela jump-cuts from scene to scene with cinematic brevity. Terse, urgent, agile, the narrative skips from life to life, mind to mind, with all the breakneck hurry of the urban crowd. One glance may seem to fix a character—Doña Matilde is “fat, dirty and pretentious”—yet when we meet the same personality again, other facets come to light. A group of core figures recur, from the hapless, idealistic poet Martín Marco and the ambitious Moisés family, with their three eligible daughters, to barman Celestino, print-shop worker Victorita, streetwalker Purita and café owner Doña Rosa, the last a bullying neighborhood bigwig who acts “like she&#39;s a regional governor.”</p><p> Mr. Womack catches the bitter comic zest of Cela&#39;s style. Dread and hardship mostly breed not kindness and solidarity but cunning, cynicism and passivity. “Madrid&#39;s a village,” we learn, one in which toxic gossip spreads fast. In “this world where everything has fallen to pieces,” bankruptcy and disgrace lurk around the corner for even the swankiest business-owners. For young women, prostitution—either overt or politely disguised—can look like the only exit. The selfless Victorita, with her consumptive boyfriend, frets that she cannot turn down an indecent proposal; Nati won&#39;t explain why she now dresses like a “princess.”</p><p> Meanwhile, postwar trauma hangs over “The Hive” like low December clouds: It&#39;s “just one of those things” for Purita to have seen her father shot and mother die, “malnourished and tubercular.” A respected physician buys 13-year-old Merche, an “unplucked fruit,” after war smashes her family: “Some of them died; others emigrated.” Cela had a reputation for misanthropic mischief, but his novel tempers its asperity with aching tenderness. There are moments in the print shop when Victorita feels the cold and “wants to cry, wants so very much to cry.” But life, and the city, must go on.</p><p> Busy but becalmed, Cela&#39;s Madrid thrums with ceaseless activity without any real movement. The hive becomes a giant jail with no remission or escape in view. Except, perhaps, for the child from a Gypsy family who sings in scene after scene. To him—like a true artist—“everything that happens is a miracle.” In the little flamenco singer&#39;s clan, people may still live “with absolute freedom and autonomy.” Elsewhere, power seems invisible and implacable. For Martín, his worries feel like fate: “It&#39;s uncontrollable, it&#39;s like the tides.”</p><p> Mr. Womack&#39;s translation boasts a lively pace and a rich demotic tang. Occasionally, his English idioms seem to swing back and forth between midcentury London and New York. So gay Señor Suárez, “alias the Snapperette,” gets called both a pansy (mostly American) and a poofter (distinctly British)—even a “muppet,” surely unheard-of on either side of the Atlantic in 1943. Whatever the epithets thrown at him, the Snapperette dares to rebel. Much more common is the obedience of the “good conformist” cop Morrazo, a Galician who “never got above himself” in a city—and a nation—now ruled in the name of piety and order.</p><p> For all its sadness, Cela&#39;s laconic, swift-moving prose pushes forward with exhilarating energy. As café-table intrigue gives way to furtive erotic rendezvous or street-corner backchat, urban bustle and banter can spark its own fleeting happiness. When night falls, Martín relishes the “deep and implacable emptiness” of his meditative walks. He finds in park benches, with their random occupiers, “an anthology of everything unpleasant and almost everything joyous.” “The Hive” hosts just such a teeming congregation of wayward needs, fears and drives. As for those “vast human enigmas,” the city can&#39;t stop to hear an answer.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Tonkin is the author of “The 100 Best Novels in Translation.”</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hive-review-fiction-madrid-faces-in-the-crowd-399854da</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-hive-review-fiction-madrid-faces-in-the-crowd-399854da<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Children’s Books: Artful Spirits and Vivid Imaginations]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Reviews of four books about creators: &#39;When Rubin Plays,&#39; &#39;Make Way,&#39; &#39;Tomfoolery!&#39; and &#39;Just Jerry.&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824420?width=600&amp;height=600" alt="Illustration by Gracey Zhang from ‘When Rubin Plays’" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Gracey Zhang from &#39;When Rubin Plays&#39; Orchard <span>Orchard</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590110164068305880"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590110164068305880"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/meghan-cox-gurdon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Meghan Cox Gurdon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 10:27 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-artful-spirits-and-vivid-imaginations-14c1e5ff"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> <strong>Creative adults</strong> may produce different sorts of work, but most seem to have had in common, as children, a certain incorrigible enthusiasm. From their earliest years, Beatrix Potter, Ezra Jack Keats, Eugene Yelchin and countless others did a terrific amount of writing or drawing, which suggests that the child whom you catch today compulsively doodling or scribbling may have a future in the arts. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/aa62e5c2-1ee9-4b05-914f-26ba6bb212c3.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The fictional young hero of Gracey Zhang&#39;s picture book “When Rubin Plays” happens to be a musician, but in his passionate enthusiasm we see the same start of a creative arc. Rubin lives in a South American village—an author&#39;s note reveals it to be Santa Ana de Velasco, in Bolivia—and loves the music of the local orchestra; it makes him “feel like flying.” Eager to join in the music making, Rubin takes up the violin. In the thick lines of Ms. Zhang&#39;s warm, inviting artwork, we see the novice persevere, producing a caterwauling that makes people smile and wince. When the orchestra conductor urges the boy to practice, Rubin takes his instrument into the forest. There the screeching sounds he makes find appreciative ears, and soon Rubin has built himself an unorthodox following. So when he brings his cacophonous style to a village concert, the audience goes quite literally wild in this sweet, if improbable, story for 4- to 8-year-olds. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"> <a href="">A Closer Look</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap"> Selections from &#39;When Rubin Plays&#39; by Gracey Zhang </h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824409/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824409/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824409/"> Orchard <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824410/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824410/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824410/"> Orchard <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824411/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824411/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824411/"> Orchard <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824412/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824412/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824412/"> Orchard <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/3100574c-5249-471d-8921-629fd0eb8ab0.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Children will read of the similar determination of a real-life artist and a real-life sculptor in “Make Way,” a picture book written by Angela Burke Kunkel and illustrated by Claire Keane. This beguiling account braids together the life stories of Robert McCloskey (1914-2003), who wrote and illustrated the classic picture book “Make Way for Ducklings,” and Nancy Schön (now 95), who some four decades ago created beloved bronze renditions of the book&#39;s mallard heroine and her eight babies for the Boston Public Garden.</p><p> “Make Way” opens with simple statements that feel like both encouragement and elegy: “In the beginning, a duck is an egg. A drawing is a blank page. A sculpture is a lump of clay.” Through the ups and downs of the paired stories, readers ages 5-8 will participate in “the building up and the taking away” as ideas are turned into art. Ms. Keane&#39;s retro pictures here have wonderful color and ebullience, bringing liveliness even to static scenes (of quiet thought, of patient studio work) and acting as a visual reminder of the exciting potentialities of invention. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"> <a href="">A Closer look</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap"> Selections from &#39;Make Way: The Story of Robert McCloskey, Nancy School, and Some Very Famous Ducklings&#39; by Angela Burke Kunkel, illustrated by Claire Keene </h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824229/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824229/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824229/"> Random House Studio <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824230/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824230/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824230/"> Random House Studio <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824231/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824231/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824231/"> Random House Studio <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824232/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824232/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824232/"> Random House Studio<span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div><p> An even more rambunctious tale describes how the picture book as we know it today began with a 19th-century Englishman named Randolph Caldecott. “Tomfoolery!”, to be published later this year, is written by Michelle Markel and illustrated by Barbara McClintock, both of whom bring brio and high good humor to Caldecott&#39;s influential personal story. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/0b38e414-e3a7-47ea-9199-9f9efc74e745.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> The book begins by presenting children&#39;s illustration as it was in the staid pre-Caldecott era: “stiff, full of pretty poses and cluttered scenery.” The young Randolph when we meet him has no idea that he will become an illustrator; he simply loves to draw. “It is too much fun. It cannot be helped,” we read. “It can happen anytime he has something to draw on—even his schoolbooks.” From an early age, Caldecott infuses his pictures with movement and, as the years pass, begins placing them in newspapers and magazines.</p><p> This spirited and joyful account is strong on the excitement of Caldecott&#39;s passion and style but vague on his career particulars; 5- to 8-year-olds (or more likely their parents) may want to check the back matter to find out where Caldecott lived, what books he illustrated and who helped him come to the world&#39;s attention. A tableau near the end of “Tomfoolery!” includes contemporary illustrators who are carrying on the zestful tradition that Caldecott began. Dan Santat and Sophie Blackall are in their midst, as well as the late Jerry Pinkney (1939-2021), master of wobbly-lined watercolors for books such as “The Lion &amp; the Mouse” and “The Little Red Hen.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"> <a href="">A Closer Look</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap"> Selections from &#39;Tomfoolery! Randolph Caldecott and the Rambunctious Coming-of-Age of Children&#39;s Books&#39; by Michelle Markel, illustrated by Barbara McClintock </h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824236/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824236/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824236/"> Chronicle <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824237/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824237/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824237/"> Chronicle <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824238/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824238/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824238/"> Chronicle <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824239/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824239/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824239/"> Chronicle<span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div><p> Pinkney, it happens, was another youthful incorrigible. So taken with drawing was he that as a boy he covered the wall beside his bed with overlapping scenes. “It didn&#39;t even matter that I was sketching over my old drawings. It only mattered that I was making pictures,” Pinkney confesses in “Just Jerry,” an illustrated coming-of-age autobiography published posthumously earlier this year. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/38141f8c-6b28-40fd-af8f-75c52ec6d851.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> In short chapters, Pinkney relates episodes from his boyhood in an all-black Philadelphia enclave, his struggles with dyslexia and his yearning to win his father&#39;s approval. Pinkney&#39;s story of his past includes moments of painful race-consciousness—he and his friends knew they were unwelcome in certain neighborhoods, and they dreaded contact with the police—but also pivotal moments of racial transcendence. In an editor&#39;s note, we learn that Pinkney had worked on his memoir for more than a decade but died before he could complete the drawings for it. In truth, the kinetic roughness of what are, in most cases, preliminary sketches has the effect of increasing the book&#39;s dynamism, because they bring readers ages 7-13 in on the process of creation rather than present them with work that is polished and, in a sense, over. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-slideshow"><div class="strap-container"><h3 class="wsj-slideshow-title strap"> <a href="">A Closer Look</a></h3><h4 class="wsj-media-dek sub-strap"> Selections from &#39;Just Jerry: How Drawing Shaped My Life&#39; by Jerry Pinkney </h4></div><div class="wsj-slideshow-wrap"><amp-carousel layout="responsive" height="400" width="600" type="slides" controls=""><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824220/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824220/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824220/"> Little, Brown <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824221/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824221/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824221/"> Little, Brown <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824222/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824222/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824222/"> Little, Brown <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div><div class="slide media-object-slideshow-slide" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><img width="undefined" height="undefined" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824223/?width=600&amp;height=400" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><input type="checkbox" class="captionToggle" id="toggle-https://images.wsj.net/im-824223/?size=custom_1600x1066https://images.wsj.net/im-824223/"> Little, Brown <span class="imageCredit"></span></p></div></amp-carousel></div></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-artful-spirits-and-vivid-imaginations-14c1e5ff</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/childrens-books-artful-spirits-and-vivid-imaginations-14c1e5ff<author><![CDATA[Meghan Cox Gurdon]]></author><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Five Best: Books on Advertising]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Selected by Ben Purkert, the author of the novel &#39;The Men Can&#39;t Be Saved.&#39; <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11636937290186344814604589627104196231722"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825028?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An image from David Ogilvy&#39;s 1951 ad campaign for Hathaway shirts.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Retro AdArchives/Alamy </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11636937290186344814604589627104196231722"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Ben Purkert</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 10:23 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-advertising-4d5e82a9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><h3> Ogilvy on Advertising</h3><p> By David Ogilvy (1983)</p><p> <strong>1.</strong> A classic never dies. And so the father of advertising, as David Ogilvy is known, will forever occupy a place on bookshelves, just as his taglines linger in the American psyche. While “Confessions of an Advertising Man” (1963) is his most famous title, “Ogilvy on Advertising” proves the most helpful guide for any newbie copywriter or graphic designer trying to break into the industry. It&#39;s a sweeping overview of how the ad biz evolved during Ogilvy&#39;s storied career, and his insights sizzle on every page: “Any fool can write a bad advertisement, but it takes a genius to keep his hands off a good one.” The book is a product of its time, and one should freely flip past those chapters that make Don Draper look like a feminist. But don&#39;t skip Ogilvy&#39;s closing pages, in which he offers bold predictions for the future, including “Billboards will be abolished” and, more laughably, “Candidates for political office will stop using dishonest advertising.” Sometimes even the world&#39;s most legendary ad man is a sucker like the rest of us.</p><h3> Then We Came to the End</h3><p> By Joshua Ferris (2007)</p><p> <strong>2.</strong> Here&#39;s how it goes: You put in a few years at an advertising agency, and then—once you&#39;re sufficiently burned out from a steady diet of business travel and binge drinking—you relocate your career to calmer waters. And yet, for the rest of your life, you carry memories of those frenzied days and nights slaving away on behalf of clients, and of the unique mix of camaraderie and competitiveness that comes with it. Joshua Ferris&#39;s bestselling novel describes that atmosphere better than any book I&#39;ve ever read. He whisks the reader into the agency world and captures its wild energy, its breakneck pace: “In those days it wasn&#39;t rare for someone to push someone else down the hall really fast in a swivel chair.” His book isn&#39;t only out for cheap thrills, though. Sometimes the daily monotony wears his characters down (“We had a meeting and when a meeting was over, we said thank you to the meeting makers for having made the meeting”) and sometimes, as when personal tragedy strikes, the mood in the office shifts dramatically. Dive into this workplace novel first and foremost for the comedy, but don&#39;t be surprised if it breaks your heart.</p><h3> You Too Can Have a Body Like Mine</h3><p> By Alexandra Kleeman (2015)</p><p> <strong>3.</strong> “There&#39;s a commercial on TV,” Alexandra Kleeman writes, “where a woman using this new citrus-based facial scrub begins to scratch at the side of her face, discovering that it has edges. 。 。 。 She grasps these edges and lifts up on them until she is peeling the whole surface of her face off with a flimsy sound like plastic wrap unsticking from itself.” It&#39;s often said that truth is stranger than fiction. Fair enough, but the most uncanny quality of this novel is how viscerally it rips the outer layers off our shared reality, exposing what lies underneath. “You Too Can Have a Body Like Mine” shines a UV light on how advertising has coiled its way into our collective brain. Paying particular attention to female body dysmorphia and disordered eating, Ms. Kleeman&#39;s debut is a testament to all the ways that commercials treat consumers as collateral damage. It&#39;s also an engrossing tale about how far people will push in the search for connection.</p><h3> A Big Life (in Advertising)</h3><p> By Mary Wells Lawrence (2002)</p><p> <strong>4.</strong> Advertising is a business built on relationships. It all depends on linking up the right copywriter with the right designer, on pairing the perfect headline with the image that makes it sing. Few people in the history of the industry have proved themselves a keener matchmaker than Mary Wells Lawrence. Her memoir details her meteoric rise, starting with her 1960s breakout campaign for Alka-Seltzer (“plop plop fizz fizz”) and charting various successes since. At a time when few women were breaking into Madison Avenue&#39;s upper ranks, Ms. Lawrence was the exception. Her secret? She would study her clients as closely as the products, adopting their hobbies as her own. It bordered on unhealthy obsession, but who says health wins in business? (“In my opinion, if you are not obsessive in the advertising business you will always work for someone else.”) “A Big Life (in Advertising” isn&#39;t all bluster and talk. She also delves into personal matters, describing her recurring battles with cancer. “In early 1987 hospitals hadn&#39;t yet transformed cancer treatment centers with good psychology and smart decorating, they were still boiling the same green robes, the waiting rooms were still heartbreaking.” Even in the midst of a serious health crisis, Ms. Lawrence never lost her eye for style.</p><h3> Subprime Attention Crisis</h3><p> By Tim Hwang (2020)</p><p> <strong>5.</strong> What causes a financial bubble? And how might we catch the next one before it bursts? According to the internet expert Tim Hwang, the answer might be right in front of our eyes: “Consider for a moment all of the advertising-supported media that you consume for free on a daily basis: podcasts, videos, articles, email newsletters, and more.” “Subprime Attention Crisis” looks closely at the ubiquity of online advertising and finds parallels to the housing market before 2008. What safeguards are in place to keep the internet afloat should the online advertising marketplace collapse? And there is good reason to think it might. Most ads bought are never seen by human eyes, and the growing popularity of ad blockers only shrinks their value further. Will companies continue pouring money into what might ultimately prove a worthless asset? Behemoths like Google and Facebook insist that the attention economy is a terrific investment, but Mr. Hwang tells a different story.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 14:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-advertising-4d5e82a9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-best-books-on-advertising-4d5e82a9<category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>图书</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[$2 Billion Default Followed Warnings to Everyone but Investors]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Beneficient executives and board directors headed for the exits over signs of trouble—long before a financial blowup that is now under investigation by the SEC and which could leave nearly 28,000 investors empty-handed <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825361/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal; Photos: Reuters, Getty Images, Bloomberg News, EagleView, Kansas Reflector <span>Alexandra Citrin-Safadi/The Wall Street Journal; Photos: Reuters, Getty Images, Bloomberg News, EagleView, Kansas Reflector</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087085"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001087085"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alexander-gladstone" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alexander Gladstone</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 28, 2023 5:29 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/2-billion-default-followed-warnings-to-everyone-but-investors-fbf13873"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Brad Heppner had the grand idea of bringing investment opportunities enjoyed by Wall Street institutions to small-fry investors. It brought misery instead.</p><p> The Texas-based financial entrepreneur named his company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/an-asset-management-merger-ended-in-bankruptcy-while-its-architect-got-174-million-11659103557?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beneficient</a> , a branding mashup of beneficial and beneficent, the quality of doing good. To bankroll his new venture, Heppner and his business partners merged it with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/retail-investors-face-1-3-billion-hit-after-asset-managers-detour-into-startups-11656066601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">GWG Holdings</a> , an established financial-services firm that sold bonds to retail investors. GWG would raise the money. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/financial-firm-beneficient-pushed-boundaries-before-bond-programs-collapse-11671757459?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beneficient</a> would put it to work. Heppner served as board chairman of both companies and recruited a cast of notable directors, including two former <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ecGmw61nR6I" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">Federal Reserve Bank presidents</a> and legendary Dallas Cowboys quarterback Roger Staubach.</p><p> From all appearances, Heppner and his team had a promising strategy: Beneficient would use money from GWG&#39;s investor base to acquire stakes in private-equity funds and other highflying assets, giving rank-and-file investors access to markets typically off limits to them. The first funds from GWG to Beneficient, $50 million, landed in June 2019. As far as board directors were concerned, Beneficient would use the money to expand the business, former directors said.</p><p> Instead, it kicked off what became one of the biggest financial blowups to strike retail investors in years.</p><p> Within weeks, Tiffany Kice, Beneficient&#39;s chief financial officer, discovered that millions of dollars went to payments for Heppner&#39;s nearly 1,500-acre east Texas ranch and his personal travel via private jet. Kice, formerly an audit partner at KPMG and CFO of Chuck E. Cheese, also found that the company had been using a faulty accounting method that would misstate revenue, according to private documents viewed by The Wall Street Journal.</p><p> What Kice learned about Beneficient&#39;s inner workings didn&#39;t, in her view, square with the best interests of investors, according to people who worked with her at the time. She repeatedly pressed Heppner for answers, and after one contentious exchange in July 2019, Kice shared a stack of financial documents with Sheldon “ Shelly” Stein, a senior board director, according to confidential court papers that allege what happened. Heppner&#39;s angry reaction had rattled her. She told Stein that she was afraid of him, the court papers show. Kice left the documents with Stein and resigned days later.</p><p> Over the next months, Kice&#39;s exit was followed by the departures of three board directors, including Stein, as well as a parade of C-suite executives—chief compliance officer, chief technology officer, operations chief and general counsel. The exits were largely driven by fears that the business risked catastrophic losses to investors while potentially benefiting Heppner, said former board directors and executives. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824325?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Brad Heppner, left, the founder and chief executive officer of Beneficient.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Tim Carpenter/Kansas Reflector</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Even after the wave of resignations, some of the remaining board directors promoted Beneficient in TV interviews and at investment conferences, helping sell GWG bonds through a nationwide network of broker-dealers. One high-profile director, former Dallas Fed President Richard Fisher, appeared in promotional videos, describing Beneficient&#39;s aim to become “an important contributor to the US economy.”</p><p> Last year, GWG defaulted on $2 billion in debt and filed for chapter 11, leaving retail investors with potential losses of as much as $1.3 billion. In separate bankruptcy and federal class-action lawsuits, investors accused board directors—including Fisher, former Atlanta Fed President Dennis Lockhart, private-equity mogul Tom Hicks and insurance executive Bruce Schnitzer</p> —of facilitating a Ponzi scheme orchestrated by Heppner. Fisher, Lockhart, Hicks and Schnitzer denied any wrongdoing in court papers and declined to comment. Heppner denied wrongdoing in court papers and through a spokesman.<p></p><p> The Securities and Exchange Commission has been investigating GWG and Beneficient since 2020, regarding Beneficient&#39;s accounting methods and payments to Heppner-related entities, according to company disclosures and people familiar with the matter. The SEC in a June 29 letter to Beneficient warned of possible civil enforcement action that would allege securities violations. Heppner, the company&#39;s founder and chief executive, received a similar letter, a company filing shows. Beneficient and Heppner said their actions were appropriate, according to the filing.</p><p> “I have always worked to maintain best-in-class governance and transparency, consistent with my fiduciary duties as a director,” Heppner said in a statement to the Journal last year. “I always relied on the counsel of independent advisers and attorneys when in the boardroom.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1980" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/eb288cd8-8e1a-4393-94c7-336a96c5ba3b-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> A Beneficient spokesman said that costs for Heppner&#39;s private jet travel and ranch were effectively paid for by a reduction in preferred equity held by Heppner-related entities. These and other related-party transactions were legal and properly disclosed, the spokesman said. He noted that Kice signed Beneficient&#39;s audit statement on June 14, 2019. Kice didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Warnings about GWG and Beneficient began in summer 2019 and spread among executives and board directors through the fall and into 2020, long before GWG&#39;s collapse. <strong>&nbsp;</strong> The only group who didn&#39;t have a clue were nearly 28,000 mom-and-pop investors, including many retirees. This account is based on securities filings, court documents, emails and interviews with former executives, former board directors and people familiar with the matter.</p><h3> Board revolt</h3><p> Heppner, 57 years old, grew up in a Mennonite community in rural Kansas and attended Southern Methodist University in Dallas. He won a scholarship established by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GS" class="company-name">Goldman Sachs</a> partner Charles Harmon Jr. , who became his mentor. Harmon later lent Heppner $1 million for one of Heppner&#39;s first deals, an $18 million buyout of asset-management firm Crossroads Group.</p><p> After Harmon died in 1997, his widow established a financial trust for Heppner with $5,000. Heppner put Crossroads and other financial ventures into the trust, which he referred to as the Harmon trust. In 2003, Heppner sold Crossroads and his other companies to Lehman Brothers for roughly $200 million. Most of the proceeds remained in the Harmon trust, and Heppner used some of the money to start Beneficient—a loan of roughly $140 million that was made through an affiliated trust. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-824502?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An aerial view from 2021 of Brad Heppner&#39;s Bradley Oaks Ranch in Bradford, Texas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: EagleView</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In addition to Kice&#39;s warnings, Stein had by August 2019 also heard from other Beneficient executives who aired concerns about Heppner&#39;s leadership, including general counsel Jessica Magee, a former SEC enforcement lawyer, and operations chief Philip Eckian, according to emails from around that time. Magee declined to comment. Eckian didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Stein, then-president of liquor distributor Southern Glazer&#39;s, began to scrutinize Beneficient&#39;s financial documents. He teamed up with two other directors— David Glaser,</p> a former senior executive at Bank of America Merrill Lynch, and Bruce Zimmerman, now chief investment officer of billionaire Ray Dalio&#39;s family office, said people familiar with the matter.<p></p><p> They looked closely at payments made to business entities related to Heppner. Stein asked board director Tom Hicks about $9 million in such payments. Hicks said he believed the payments were proper, according to an email to Stein viewed by the Journal.</p><p> Zimmerman told others on the board in an August 2019 email that he was troubled by the payments to Heppner-related parties. Stein agreed. “Cash flow is a major problem and it is unacceptable to make payments from GWG to BEN to related parties,” he wrote in response. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825362?width=700&amp;height=700" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A photo taken during a Beneficient event at Bradley Oaks Ranch. Brad Heppner is seated on left, wearing glasses.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Heppner urged payment on the loan from the Harmon trust affiliate that had funded Beneficient, emphasizing that it was a contractual obligation. “Those trusts are fed up and want to be paid out,” Heppner said in a July 15, 2019, email to Hicks that was forwarded to Stein. “We need to be very careful on this, because they have been accommodating. That said they aren&#39;t going to be so willing anymore.”</p><p> Most of the board directors didn&#39;t realize at the time that Heppner had a substantial financial interest in the Harmon trust and its affiliates, former directors said. Heppner is a beneficiary of the trusts, which lend money to Heppner&#39;s other business ventures, according to a recent securities filing.</p><p> Heppner pressed ahead with fundraising efforts. In a Sept. 7, 2019, email to directors, he said bond sales for August had grown to nearly $50 million. “GWG doesn&#39;t want to get ahead of itself,” he wrote, “but if GWG continues to see similar levels of interest in September, I hope to be updating you about a new all-time monthly high in sales very soon.”</p><p> He noted in the email that Staubach, the former Cowboys quarterback, was scheduled to give the keynote address at an Oct. 15, 2019 finance conference in Las Vegas. “Going forward we will continue to lean on you, our directors, to be ambassadors for Ben and GWG&#39;s revamped bond program,” he wrote. Staubach declined to comment.</p><p> Board directors Glaser, Zimmerman and Stein became increasingly skeptical that Beneficient&#39;s strategy of acquiring stakes in private-equity funds from individuals would generate enough revenue to repay GWG bond investors. Fisher and Zimmerman asked Heppner for the company&#39;s financial projections in a Sept. 21, 2019, email. Heppner provided forecasts showing annual revenue was expected to grow from near zero to at least $1.7 billion by 2025.</p><p> Matters came to a head at an Oct. 10, 2019, meeting at Beneficient&#39;s headquarters in Dallas. Zimmerman, Glaser and Stein weren&#39;t persuaded that there was a basis for the bullish projections during tense discussions with Heppner, Hicks and Schnitzer. Zimmerman resigned and left the room. Glaser and Stein quit the board within days.</p><p> Two other directors, former CNBC anchor Michelle Caruso-Cabrera and Staubach, resigned months later. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/678ef8fc-4ee5-4cb5-b891-d30f942dd92c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><h3> &#39;Violation of trust&#39;</h3><p> Bond sales continued to climb through 2020. In October that year, the SEC notified GWG, the parent company of Beneficient, that it was under investigation. The federal agency requested details about Beneficient&#39;s accounting and valuation practices, as well as its transactions with related parties.</p><p> In July 2021, the SEC concluded that the accounting method Beneficient had been using was incorrect: the firm had been making loans to its own subsidiaries and counting the interest it received as revenue. That was a problem Kice had noted. Bond sales were halted until the companies corrected their financial statements.</p><p> GWG didn&#39;t disclose the extent of losses in Beneficient&#39;s private-equity investments until the companies restated their financial statements in November 2021, according to securities filings. That also was the first time they disclosed the SEC probe.</p><p> By then, GWG was on the verge of collapse. When the company tried to relaunch its bond-selling program, the SEC warned the company&#39;s broker-dealers that they, too, would be investigated if they continued to sell the bonds. Around that time, Beneficient separated as an independent company. With bond sales frozen, GWG failed to pay interest payments due in January 2022 and filed for chapter 11 that April.</p><p> In the years since linking up with Beneficient, GWG sold $1.3 billion in bonds, with much of the proceeds used to repay GWG&#39;s past investors. Beneficient received $230 million from GWG and paid at least $174 million to entities associated with Heppner. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-825081?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Clifford Day, a retiree in Boca Raton, Fla.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Grace Day</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Clifford Day, a 74-year-old retired social worker in Boca Raton, Fla., said that following the GWG-Beneficient merger he had invested around $220,000, a significant portion of his life savings, into GWG bonds on the recommendation of his financial adviser. “This violation of trust has shaken me to my core,” he said after GWG defaulted.</p><p> Day&#39;s broker, David Arlein, said he had been impressed by the presence of board directors such as Fisher, the former Dallas Fed president, and Staubach, who led the Cowboys to two Super Bowl victories.</p><p> Fisher, Lockhart, Hicks and Schnitzer, who remained as Beneficient directors after at least five colleagues resigned, have each received more than $1.7 million in compensation for their years of service, according to securities filings.</p><p> The bankruptcy court formed two trusts to try to return some of the $1.3 billion owed to GWG bond investors. One trust will aim to sell the roughly 170 million shares of Beneficient that GWG owns. The other trust is weighing litigation against Beneficient and its current and former directors.</p><p> Last month, Beneficient went public in a merger with a special-purpose acquisition company. The company said in securities filings and marketing materials that the transaction would value it at $3.5 billion. Beneficient ended up raising around $8 million through the SPAC deal. Its stock closed at $2.14 on Thursday, down more than 85% from its opening price on June 8.</p><p> On July 17, the company announced the launch of an online platform to encourage investors in private-equity funds to swap their assets for Beneficient stock.</p><p> Write to Alexander Gladstone at <a href="mailto:alexander.gladstone@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">alexander.gladstone@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 28 Jul 2023 09:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/2-billion-default-followed-warnings-to-everyone-but-investors-fbf13873</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/2-billion-default-followed-warnings-to-everyone-but-investors-fbf13873<author><![CDATA[Alexander Gladstone]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> leder</category><category>信托/基金/金融工具</category><category>保险</category><category>Financial Investment Services</category><category> Security Brokering/Dealing</category><category> Diversified Holding Companies</category><category> Business/Consumer Services</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>企业犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>Bankruptcy</category><category> Corporate Funding</category><category> Ownership Changes</category><category> Corporate Actions</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Corporate Financial Difficulty</category><category> Private Equity/Venture Funding</category><category> Securities Regulations</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Financial Crime</category><category> Fraud</category><category>证券欺诈</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>有益的</category><category>BENF</category><category> GWG Holdings</category><category> GWGHQ</category><category> Brad Heppner</category><category>企业犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>bankruptcy</category><category>企业